These investigations imply that PANI/CDs film should achieve a higher IR modulation contrast and a faster switching speed in comparison with the PANI film. Therefore, the IR electrochromic performance of the PANI/CDs film and PANI film were performed by recording their IR emittance curves under different potentials (Fig. 4
                     ), and the summarized results are listed in Table 1
                     .

The PANI/CDs infrared electrochromic device (IR-ECD) was fabricated according to illustrated Scheme 1. The two PANI/CDs films were employed as the EC layer and ion storage layer, respectively. The copper tapes were used as two individual electrodes, while the middle gel electrolyte (LiClO4/PC) solution was used for the electrolyte layer. To evaluate the IR modulation ability, the emittance curves of the PANI/CDs IR-ECD at colored and bleached states were measured upon the potential of 0.8 V and −0.8 V at the wavelength of 2.5–25 μm. As shown in Fig. 5
                      (a), the color of the PANI/CDs IR-ECD changed from yellow to atrovirens in the voltage positive conversion process. It presents Δε values of 0.39, 0.41, and 0.37 in wavelength ranges of 3–5 μm, 8–14 μm, and 2.5–25 μm, respectively. Noting that the present Δε of 0.41 in 8–14 μm is superior to the previous acid-doped PANI device [14–16] (Table 2
                     ).
